Comment: King's pawn open.  My default.
Apparently, this is called the Robatsch defence, but I'm not very familiar with it.
I wanted to protect the main diagonal because I've gotten burned and lost my rooks early in some previous games.  Planning on playing 3.d4
I found this to be an odd move.  This does open up the light diagonal, but it's already closed off by my pawn on e4.
Now I take control of the center squares and free up my dark bishop.
Again, I don't really get this move.  He may be trying to force me to protect my pawn, but it really accomplishes very little.
Protecting my pawn.  In hindsight, 4.f3 probably was a better choice, but it was a blitz game and I didn't think this move over for a long time.  Oh well, this still worked well enough.
Now he starts developing some of his pieces.
Now I start to set up what I like to call the "Flying V".  There's probably a more technical name than that, but I like my name for it.
He saves his knight and gives me the chance to truly set up the flying V.
A development move.  Opens up the dark bishop and gets my knight into an attacking position.

No idea why he made this move.  He leaves an unprotected pawn right in my bishop's path and also likely destroys his ability to king-side castle.  This does nothing for development, and will most likely end up only hurting him.
... I should've played 7.Bxg5.  I looked back right after I made this move and facepalmed immediately.  I gave him a free out for his previous bad move.  I'll give myself a "?" on this move.
Now the pawn move makes sense, even though I should have never let this move happen.
I decided not to let his knight stay comfortable.  I decided to threaten it immediately and try to get it on the move.
He refuses to move, and instead beefs up his defenses.
No rest for his knight, so I up the pressure.
Another "?" move, where he leaves an unprotected piece directly in my line of attack.  I wasn't going to let it slide this time.
Boom, early material and development advantage.
Don't know what he was going for here.  Not a bad move, but it really accomplishes nothing.
